6. Translation classes

Not all translations are equal. Pantheon should distinguish them.

Class I — Syntax-preserving translation

Same structure, different syntax.

Examples:
	•	JSON ↔ YAML
	•	Markdown ↔ HTML
	•	TOML ↔ INI-like config

Low semantic risk.

Class II — Structure-preserving translation

Different syntax and layout, same semantic structure.

Examples:
	•	CSV ↔ SQL table
	•	OpenAPI spec ↔ typed client stubs
	•	UML-ish diagram ↔ object model

Moderate semantic risk.

Class III — Invariant-preserving translation

Different form, same core meaning.

Examples:
	•	prose notes ↔ formal checklist
	•	strategy memo ↔ workflow graph
	•	story ↔ doctrine node set

Higher risk, needs explicit invariant declaration.

Class IV — Generative rehydration

Sparse structure expanded into a richer artifact.

Examples:
	•	schema → UI
	•	meeting notes → roadmap
	•	invariant phrase → full doctrine writeup

Highest creative power, highest distortion risk.

⸻

7. The conservation law

A transformation should explicitly declare:

What is preserved
	•	entities
	•	relations
	•	order
	•	constraints
	•	tone
	•	intent
	•	behavior
	•	semantic invariant

What may change
	•	syntax
	•	verbosity
	•	ordering
	•	field names
	•	presentation
	•	compression ratio

What may be lost
	•	comments
	•	formatting
	•	ambiguity
	•	emotional texture
	•	provenance
	•	unstated assumptions

This is crucial.

Because translation without a stated conservation law is just mutation.

⸻

8. Pantheon transformation contract

Every transformation should answer five questions:

source_representation:
target_representation:
preserved_invariant:
allowed_losses:
validation_method:

Example:

source_representation: json
target_representation: yaml
preserved_invariant: hierarchical key/value data and scalar values
allowed_losses:
  - whitespace formatting
  - ordering if semantically irrelevant
validation_method:
  - parse equivalence
  - schema validation

For prose → spec:

source_representation: design memo
target_representation: structured schema
preserved_invariant: entities, relations, constraints, workflow order
allowed_losses:
  - rhetorical style
  - metaphorical language
validation_method:
  - entity coverage check
  - constraint match
  - operator review


